<DOC><DOCNO> AP881001-0028 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-10-01-88 0435EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-Nicaragua     10-01 0213</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Nicaragua,0219</SECOND><HEAD>Contras Say Sandinistas Planning Offensive</HEAD><DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Nicaraguan rebels accused the leftistgovernment of amassing troops and artillery for a major offensiveas another government extension to a six-month cease-fire went intoeffect today.   Radio Liberacion, the rebels' clandestine radio, also saidFriday the government provoked ``incidents with the Honduran army''along Nicaragua's northern border.   On Thursday, Nicaragua's Sandinista government announced itsfifth unilateral extension of the cease-fire that began March 23,though peace talks stalled June 9. The ban on offensive operationsruns until Oct. 31.   The U.S.-backed rebels, known as Contras, have said the truce isindefinite. Their Radio Liberacion broadcast said the Sandinistaswere taking advantage of the cease-fire to prepare the offensive.   After U.S. military aid to the Contras ended in February, thebulk of the rebel force retreated to camps on Honduran territorynear the frontier. Both rebels and Sandinistas allege frequenttruce violations.   Nicaragua's acting foreign minister, Javier Chamorro Mora, senta formal protest to Honduras Thursday in which he accused theHonduran armed forces of six border incursions and three violationsof Nicaraguan airspace in September.   A report Thursday in the official Sandinista newspaper Barricadasaid Nicaraguan troops fired on the intruding aircraft in onerecent incident.   Honduras denied the reports.</TEXT></DOC>